Partly, yes.

Humans inherit many limits:

* biology,
* time,
* mortality,
* environment,
* circumstance,
* history.

But we also construct additional layers ourselves:

* beliefs,
* habits,
* identities,
* fears,
* ambitions,
* social systems,
* narratives,
* expectations,
* and self-concepts.

Some of those structures protect and stabilize us.
Some quietly become prisons long after they stop serving us.

A lot of growth is really:

learning which constraints are fundamental,
and which are negotiable.

People often discover they were obeying:

* assumptions,
* inherited scripts,
* social inertia,
* or old survival adaptations

more than actual necessity.

At the same time, removing every boundary doesn’t produce meaning automatically either.

The interesting tension is that humans are both:

* shaped by structures,
    and
* capable of reshaping them.

That’s why:

* education changes trajectories,
* therapy changes behavioral loops,
* training changes capability,
* culture evolves,
* and technology expands previously impossible spaces.

So I’d phrase it less as:

“we are trapped by limits of our own making,”

and more:

“we continuously participate in constructing the architectures we live inside.”

Some deserve reinforcement.
Some deserve redesign.
Some deserve demolition.